| Fear               | 0.256      | 0.135     | 0.10 | 0.50 | ‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà                                       |
| Fantasy            | 0.175      | 0.104     | 0.00 | 0.30 | ‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà                                          |
| **MC-SCI**         | **0.091**  | 0.036     | 0.046| 0.154| N/A                                              |

The high standard deviation for **Hope** (0.236) and **Resentment** (0.204) is particularly noteworthy. Evidence suggests this is driven by wildly different applications of these themes. For example, Hope is used both for aspirational, unifying visions [10] and for cynical, threatening predictions [11]. Similarly, speakers either explicitly reject grievance [12] or build their entire argument around it, driving Resentment scores to opposite extremes.

#### **Key Correlation Patterns**
The correlation matrix reveals structural relationships between character dimensions, exposing common rhetorical strategies.

| Correlation Pair                          | `r` value | Strength     | Interpretation & Evidence                                                                                                                                                                                          |
| ----------------------------------------- | --------- | ------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Truth** ‚Üî **Justice**                   | **+0.90** | Very Strong  | Speakers frequently link appeals to factual accuracy with calls for fairness. Arguments for justice are framed as the logical outcome of a truth-seeking process, as seen in speeches on criminal justice [6] and impeachment [7]. |
| **Resentment** ‚Üî **Fear**                 | **+0.74** | Strong       | Rhetoric centered on past grievances is strongly associated with appeals to future anxiety. Speakers use historical injustices to stoke a "constant fear of a police state," creating a powerful emotional pairing [8, 9].        |
| **Dignity** ‚Üî **Fantasy**                 | **-0.92** | Very Strong  | An exceptionally strong negative correlation suggests that rhetoric grounded in respect for human dignity is also firmly rooted in reality. High-dignity speech avoids unrealistic promises and magical thinking, instead referencing historical facts and progress [5]. |
| **Dignity** ‚Üî **Hope**                    | **+0.89** | Very Strong  | Rhetoric emphasizing universal dignity is highly correlated with a constructive, optimistic vision. This pairing forms the backbone of inspiring and unifying political discourse [2, 10].                                        |
| **Tribalism** ‚Üî **Fantasy**               | **+0.75** | Strong       | In contrast to Dignity, appeals to group loyalty are strongly linked to unrealistic promises. This suggests a rhetorical strategy where in-group preference is justified by a fantastical vision of the future or a distorted view of reality [3]. |
| **Hope** ‚Üî **Manipulation**               | **-0.70** | Strong       | Authentic, constructive Hope is negatively correlated with deceptive rhetoric. This highlights the difference between genuine optimism and the false hope often generated through manipulative tactics. |

